I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 367535130
Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

[{"sha":"680028173f0e522a7787f5886430179dff1f8e0d","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updating Dockerfile.rocm to use ROCm 4.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/680028173f0e522a7787f5886430179dff1f8e0d"},{"sha":"eae914bf3852fe23d719ff41b7f2357452f905f7","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updating CI scripts to use ROCm 4.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/eae914bf3852fe23d719ff41b7f2357452f905f7"},{"sha":"e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switching ROCm TF to use the new hipfft library (instead of rocfft).

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/linalg:linear_operator_circulant_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:dct_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:mel_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:mfcc_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:spectral_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/ops/parallel_for:control_flow_ops_test_gpu
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0"},{"sha":"e0ab1ce9b6640da7730bf48b095268448b844c82","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":" Updating the mapping of GCN Arch Name tokens to feature strings.

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

[{"sha":"b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Add post-commit hook (#21183)

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switching ROCm TF to use the new hipfft library (instead of rocfft).

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

```

//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:mfcc_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:spectral_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/ops/parallel_for:control_flow_ops_test_gpu
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0"},{"sha":"e0ab1ce9b6640da7730bf48b095268448b844c82","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":" Updating the mapping of GCN Arch Name tokens to feature strings.

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

(Notice the dash "-" is gone from "+sram-ecc")

The LLVM version being picked up by TF in this branch ( `develop-upstream-QA-rocm42` ) seems have changes withing it (as compared to the version being picked up in the `develop-upstream-QA-rocm41` branch), which require this change in the mapping.

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

[{"sha":"316aa368654427270a53543cd3f4952746374596","author":{"name":"Andrey Marchenko","email":"8158629700c049a80bb8c08eb54abd93a300e784@gmail.com"},"message":"[Scheduler] Fix de-opt caused by out-of-bounds access (#21147)

Scheduler's heap implementation sometimes accesses indices that are out
of bounds (larger than the size of the array). This causes a VM de-opt.

This change fixes the de-opt by always checking the index before
accessing the array. In exchange, we can remove the typecheck on the
returned element.

Background: https://v8.dev/blog/elements-kinds#avoid-reading-beyond-the-length-of-the-array

Co-authored-by: Andrew Clark <git@andrewclark.io>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/316aa368654427270a53543cd3f4952746374596"},{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that components layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the components layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse chartsI believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"},{"sha":"172e89b4bf0ec5ee5738af0156d90b0deef4d494","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"Reland Remove redundant initial of isArray (#21188)

Taking the same approach as was taken in containerd

The new library has a slightly different output;

- keys at the same level are sorted alphabetically
- empty sections not omitted (`proxy_plugins`, `stream_processors`, `timeouts`),
  which could possibly be be addressed with an "omitempty" in containerd's struct.
- empty slices are not omitted (`imports`, `required_plugins`)

After sorting the "before" configuration the diff looks like this:

```patch
diff --git a/config-before-sorted.toml b/config-after.toml
index cc771ce7ab..43a727f589 100644
--- a/config-before-sorted.toml
+++ b/config-after.toml
@@ -1,6 +1,8 @@
 disabled_plugins = ["cri"]
+imports = []
 oom_score = 0
 plugin_dir = ""
+required_plugins = []
 root = "/var/lib/docker/containerd/daemon"
 state = "/var/run/docker/containerd/daemon"
 version = 0
@@ -37,6 +39,12 @@ version = 0
     shim = "containerd-shim"
     shim_debug = true

+[proxy_plugins]
+
+[stream_processors]
+
+[timeouts]
+
 [ttrpc]
   address = ""
   gid = 0
```

[{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0"},{"sha":"e0ab1ce9b6640da7730bf48b095268448b844c82","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":" Updating the mapping of GCN Arch Name tokens to feature strings.

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

(Notice the dash "-" is gone from "+sram-ecc")

The LLVM version being picked up by TF in this branch ( `develop-upstream-QA-rocm42` ) seems have changes withing it (as compared to the version being picked up in the `develop-upstream-QA-rocm41` branch), which require this change in the mapping.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

(Notice the dash "-" is gone from "+sram-ecc")

The LLVM version being picked up by TF in this branch ( `develop-upstream-QA-rocm42` ) seems have changes withing it (as compared to the version being picked up in the `develop-upstream-QA-rocm41` branch), which require this change in the mapping.

[{"sha":"680028173f0e522a7787f5886430179dff1f8e0d","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updating Dockerfile.rocm to use ROCm 4.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/680028173f0e522a7787f5886430179dff1f8e0d"},{"sha":"eae914bf3852fe23d719ff41b7f2357452f905f7","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updating CI scripts to use ROCm 4.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/eae914bf3852fe23d719ff41b7f2357452f905f7"},{"sha":"e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switching ROCm TF to use the new hipfft library (instead of rocfft).

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/linalg:linear_operator_circulant_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:dct_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:mel_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:mfcc_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:spectral_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/ops/parallel_for:control_flow_ops_test_gpu
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0"},{"sha":"e0ab1ce9b6640da7730bf48b095268448b844c82","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":" Updating the mapping of GCN Arch Name tokens to feature strings.

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"}]

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 367535130
Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

[{"sha":"b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools: Add post-commit hook (#21183)

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"}]

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

(Notice the dash "-" is gone from "+sram-ecc")

The LLVM version being picked up by TF in this branch ( `develop-upstream-QA-rocm42` ) seems have changes withing it (as compared to the version being picked up in the `develop-upstream-QA-rocm41` branch), which require this change in the mapping.

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 367535130
Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

Tracked Fibers are called "updaters" and are exposed to DevTools via a 'memoizedUpdaters' property on the ReactFiberRoot. The implementation of this feature follows a vaguely similar approach as interaction tracing, but does not require reference counting since there is no subscriptions API.

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"}]

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

Tracked Fibers are called "updaters" and are exposed to DevTools via a 'memoizedUpdaters' property on the ReactFiberRoot. The implementation of this feature follows a vaguely similar approach as interaction tracing, but does not require reference counting since there is no subscriptions API.

This change is in support of a new DevTools Profiler feature that shows which Fiber(s) scheduled the selected commit in the Profiler.

All changes have been gated behind a new feature flag, 'enableUpdaterTracking', which is enabled for Profiling builds by default. For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

```

//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests/signal:spectral_ops_test
//tensorflow/python/ops/parallel_for:control_flow_ops_test_gpu
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/e253ebbaaa79fd6014ebcf426d989f950d86aea0"},{"sha":"e0ab1ce9b6640da7730bf48b095268448b844c82","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":" Updating the mapping of GCN Arch Name tokens to feature strings.

Prior to this commit, the GCN Arch Name "gfx908:+sramecc", would get mapped to
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sram-ecc"}

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

(Notice the dash "-" is gone from "+sram-ecc")

The LLVM version being picked up by TF in this branch ( `develop-upstream-QA-rocm42` ) seems have changes withing it (as compared to the version being picked up in the `develop-upstream-QA-rocm41` branch), which require this change in the mapping.

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

and containerd is switching to this project instead, so start
moving our code as well.

This patch only changes the binary used during validation (tbh,
we could probably remove this validation step, but leaving that
for now).

I manually verified that the hack/verify/toml still works by adding a commit
that makes the MAINTAINERS file invalid;

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/1d4a2734878610cb3b1f9389d9ab47a7f9d923b4"},{"sha":"2a7c1cc1d6de7dd0dfd1a628e8a4be5b4949e103","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"libcontainerd/supervisor: replace BurntSushi/toml with pelletier/go-toml

Taking the same approach as was taken in containerd

The new library has a slightly different output;

- keys at the same level are sorted alphabetically
- empty sections not omitted (`proxy_plugins`, `stream_processors`, `timeouts`),
  which could possibly be be addressed with an "omitempty" in containerd's struct.
- empty slices are not omitted (`imports`, `required_plugins`)

After sorting the "before" configuration the diff looks like this:

```patch
diff --git a/config-before-sorted.toml b/config-after.toml
index cc771ce7ab..43a727f589 100644
--- a/config-before-sorted.toml
+++ b/config-after.toml
@@ -1,6 +1,8 @@
 disabled_plugins = ["cri"]
+imports = []
 oom_score = 0
 plugin_dir = ""
+required_plugins = []
 root = "/var/lib/docker/containerd/daemon"
 state = "/var/run/docker/containerd/daemon"
 version = 0
@@ -37,6 +39,12 @@ version = 0
     shim = "containerd-shim"
     shim_debug = true

+[proxy_plugins]
+
+[stream_processors]
+
+[timeouts]
+
 [ttrpc]
   address = ""
   gid = 0
```

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.
    I've also added a unit test to guard against this regressing in the future.

    * Doing this in flushPassiveEffectsImpl seemed simplest, since there are so many places we flush passive effects. Is there any potential problem with this though?","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/b38ac13f946ad305ead05a6a83511549db27322e"},{"sha":"6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830","author":{"name":"inokawa","email":"6d6d97e4c4e329beca81f7ad0171ac737338a3c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix typo in comment (#21214)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/6ea749170b6d59b8dfb8bbbb8d05d986099e7830"},{"sha":"dc108b0f55387c811899aeb92e583294b0707b1c","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Track which fibers scheduled the current render work (#15658)

This change is in support of a new DevTools Profiler feature that shows which Fiber(s) scheduled the selected commit in the Profiler.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/42ef2c5036f5131fbabf7389ac7efa049cd63cd2"},{"sha":"2834f842ee25c081abad0dc1473dd7c65ce94cb8","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use containerd's apparmor package to detect if apparmor can be used

The runc/libcontainer apparmor package on master no longer checks if apparmor_parser
is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moxonsghost/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"}]

[{"sha":"ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for ROCm CSB breakage - 210329

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

Change-Id: I5e8be0b4c88aa770365c2566cf4ecac0101bfde8","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lambdaxymox/tensorflow/commits/7b896b7e2d4066130d3d2a609cdfbb8e231229d5"},{"sha":"5a737ab3a1cc9f85c2d99af994ba016c10380e10","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"PR #47833: Lazy load optional modules to speedup pip package import (re-commit)

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/47833

This PR lazy loads optional external Python modules to speedup initial import times of the TF pip package.

These changes speedup initial import by roughly **24%**:

modules | percentage of TF import
---|---
kubernetes | 14.5 %
pandas | 6.9 %
scipy | 2.6 %

This partially addresses #37729, but import times are still quite slow. A large chunk is spent importing the `tf.compat` which I don't think is used a lot by the average user, so it would be great if this could be lazy loaded as well in the future.

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

This commit changes the mapping to the following
* { target : "gfx908", feature_string : "+sramecc"}

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

I recently added UI for the Profiler's commit and post-commit durations to the DevTools, but I made two pretty silly oversights:

    1. I used the commit hook (called after mutation+layout effects) to read both the layout and passive effect durations. This is silly because passive effects may not have flushed yet git at this point.
    2. I didn't reset the values on the HostRoot node, so they accumulated with each commit.

    This commitR addresses both issues:

    1. First it adds a new DevTools hook, onPostCommitRoot*, to be called after passive effects get flushed. This gives DevTools the opportunity to read passive effect durations (if the build of React being profiled supports it).
    2. Second the work loop resets these durations (on the HostRoot) after calling the post-commit hook so address the accumulation problem.

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.

Manually confirmed with the steps outlined in #47575 that exception
related symbols are no longer part of the keyword_benchmark binary when
build with the Xtensa toolchain.

Manually tested the size with:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Without this change:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  70912	  40212	  24856	 135980	  2132c	tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

With this change:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  88712	    384	  22704	 111800	  1b4b8	tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

While what goes in the text and data sections has changed, the overall
binary size is reduced by ~24KB.

Also confirmed that the cycles for the keyword benchmark are unaffected:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade run_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner took 159001 ticks (159 ms).

QUANTIZE took 800 ticks (0 ms).
SVDF took 4753 ticks (4 ms).

SVDF took 3054 ticks (3 ms).
FULLY_CONNECTED took 1091 ticks (1 ms).
SOFTMAX took 749 ticks (0 ms).

KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 342530 ticks (342 ms)
```

And all the unit tests pass:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade test -j8
```

Change-Id: I5a89b41f600d6e03c75366fb41e1b5fdbefe9f1a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sunshinemyson/tensorflow/commits/de5bfc8bb62ee0b73f0d84e9f7f37b83475f4371"},{"sha":"0029a3c377e9e0e05d6a381dda1ac418f4357e9f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug when LossScaleOptimizer and gradient_aggregator were used.

Before, if there were multiple processes each with a LossScaleOptimizer, and the inner optimizer had a custom gradient_aggregator to aggregate gradients across the processes, the LossScaleOptimizers in the processes could become out of sync. In particular, if a strict subset of replicas encountered NaN gradients, only the LossScaleOptimizers with NaN gradients would skip the step, while the LossScaleOptimizers with finite gradients would still apply gradients

Resolves https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46863. Horovod was broken with LossScaleOptimizer in TF 2.4 due to this bug, but they patched in a workaround. With this fix, the workaround will not be necessary in TF 2.5.

The issue was caused by the fact the gradients were checked for NaNs before they were all-reduced. This was handled correctly with tf.distribute.Strategy but not with an arbitrary gradient_aggregator. Now, the gradients are all-reduced before they are checked for NaNs, which means if any replica has NaNs, they all will have NaNs.

This potentially will allow better performance in the future as well, as it allows earlier-computed gradients to be all-reduced in parallel with the computation of later-computed gradients.

Change-Id: I3fe993b3e7320c070185f597ab99d013c322903e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/45f42bb55a645c2f64583cf4f6d9f7713e210274"},{"sha":"948d067d0c9d5a99e5ad5e672bb713a578c80a26","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Skip float ops used by NumericVerify op from QuantizationPass

float ops can remain in the graph when numeric_verify is enabled. This becomes a problem when a float op left in the graph is visited again (i.e. ADD op that gets dequantized input from two results). In that case, the quantization pass does not visit some of the ops from the split path, leaving some ops not quantized.

When numeric verify is enabled, skipping this float ops makes the whole graph correctly quantized with NumericVerify ops.
